Introduction:

Merton and Scholes received the 1997 Nobel Prize in Economic Sciences for their work with the Black-Sholes model. Its formula provides a great way to hedge options by buying or selling the underlying asset in order to mitigate risks for investments. "The Greeks" measure the sensitivity of the value of a derivative or a portfolio to changes in parameter value(s) while holding the other parameters fixed. They are partial derivatives of the price with respect to the parameter values, they will be modelled in this paper in order to hedge with $\Delta$ and $\Delta \Gamma$.

Call Option: Delta Neutral.

An options position can be hedged with one or various options with a delta opposite to that of the current position. The objective is to make the portfolio have an accumulated $\Delta$ of 0, a term which is widely known as: achieve Delta Neutral.
Doing so will minimize the options portfolio price movements from underlying asset fluctuations.

When selling an option, Delta hedging allows the investor to anticipate to unfavorauble market conditions and to protect profits from past operations.
A disadvantage for portfolio accumulated returns are the trading costs, so we need to have them in mind as well. It is important to note as well that the portfolio can suddenly get to be over-hedged by the market.

Opened positions should be constantly and appropiately rebalanced with the help of several techniques:

Greeks:

1° order¶

$\Delta = \frac{\partial V}{\partial S}$

$\Theta = \frac{-\partial V}{\partial r}$

$\nu = \frac{\partial V}{\partial \sigma}$

$\rho = \frac{\partial V}{\partial r}$

$\epsilon = \frac{\partial V}{\partial q}$

2° order¶

$\Gamma = \frac{\partial^2 V}{\partial S^2}$

Vanna = $\frac{\partial^2 V}{\partial S \partial \sigma}$

Charm = $\frac{\partial^2 V}{\partial \tau \partial S}$

Vomma = $\frac{\partial^2 V}{\partial \sigma^2}$

Veta = $\frac{\partial^2 V}{\partial \sigma \partial r}$

Vera = $\frac{\partial^2 V}{\partial \sigma \partial r}$

Calculating $\Delta$¶

Steps:

  1. Calculate Call fair price.

$V_t=S_t N\left(d_1\right)-K e^{-r(t-t)} N\left(d_2\right)$

  1. Obtain the Partial Derivative with respect to $S_t$

$\frac{\delta V t}{\delta S_t}=\frac{\delta S_t}{\delta S_t} N\left(d_1\right) + \frac{\delta N\left(d_1\right)}{\delta d_1} \cdot S t \cdot \frac{\delta d_1}{\delta S_t} - Ke^{-r(t-t)} N'\left(d_2\right) $

  1. Apply the chain rule property:

    $d[f(x) g(z)] = \frac{\delta f^{\prime}(x)}{\delta x} g(z)+\frac{g^{\prime}(z)}{d z} \cdot f(x) \cdot \frac{\delta z}{\delta x}$

$\frac{\delta V_t}{\delta S_t} = N\left(d_1\right) + \frac{d_1}{\delta S_t} \biggl [S_t N'(d1) - Ke^{-r(t-t)} N'\left(d_2\right) \biggr ]$

  1. Apply property:

    $\frac{\delta d_1}{\delta S_t} = \frac{\delta d_2}{\delta S_t}$

$Ke^{-r(t-t)} N'\left(d_2\right) = S_t N'(d1)$

$\biggl [S_t N'(d1) - Ke^{-r(t-t)} N'\left(d_2\right) \biggr ] = 0$

$\frac{\delta V_t}{\delta S_t} = N\left(d_1\right) + \frac{d_1}{\delta S_t} [0]$

$\frac{\delta V_t}{\delta S_t} = N\left(d_1\right)$

  • $X \sim \mathcal{N}(\mu,\,\sigma^{2})$

  • $N$ is the standard normal distribution function CDF.

Result:¶

$\delta = N(d_{1})$

Modeling Portfolio $\Pi$:¶

$\Delta$ hedging¶

Steps:

Following the Black-Scholes model we will consider the stock price $S_t$ with the dynamics of the $V_t$ derivative using $S_t$ as the underlying. The Black-Scholes equation affirms that under conditions of no arbitrage, any derivative shows a behavior that satistfies the partial differential equation:

  1. Derivatives partial differential equation.

$dV = \sigma S \frac{\partial V}{\partial S}dW + \bigg( \mu S \frac{\partial V}{\partial S} + \frac{1}{2}\sigma ^2 S^2 \frac{\partial^2 V}{\partial S^2} + \frac{\partial V}{\partial t} \bigg)dt$.

  1. Price movements equation:

$ dS = \mu S dt + \sigma S dW $

  1. Change expression and replace terms:

Assuming that the portfolio $\Pi$ has $x$ units of $S$ portffolio dynamics can then be expressed as:

$ d\Pi = dV - x dS$

Replacing $dV$ and x $dS$ in the value of the portfolio, the model can be expressed as:

$$d\Pi = \sigma S \frac{\partial V}{\partial S}dW + \bigg( \mu S \frac{\partial V}{\partial S} + \frac{1}{2}\sigma^2 S^2 \frac{\partial^2 V}{\partial S^2} + \frac{\partial V}{\partial t} \bigg)dt - x \bigg(\mu S dt + \sigma S dW \bigg)$$
  1. Group $ d\Pi$ by common terms and reduce:
$$ d\Pi = \bigg(\mu S \frac{\partial V}{\partial S} + \frac{1}{2}\sigma^2 S^2 \frac{\partial^2 V}{\partial S^2} + \frac{\partial V}{\partial t} -x\mu S \bigg)dt + \bigg(\sigma S \frac{\partial V}{\partial S} - x \sigma S \bigg)dW $$

This can be reduced to:

$$ d\Pi = \bigg(\mu S \bigg(\frac{\partial V}{\partial S} - x \bigg)+ \frac{1}{2}\sigma^2 S^2 \frac{\partial^2 V}{\partial S^2} + \frac{\partial V}{\partial t} \bigg)dt + \sigma S \bigg(\frac{\partial V}{\partial S} - x \bigg)dW $$

If equal $x = \frac{\partial V}{\partial S}$ we can cancel the following terms:

$$ d\Pi = \bigg(\mu S [0] + \frac{1}{2}\sigma^2 S^2 \frac{\partial^2 V}{\partial S^2} + \frac{\partial V}{\partial t} \bigg)dt + \sigma S (0)dW $$

Finally, the dynamics of the portfolio are modelled by:

$d\Pi = \bigg(\frac{1}{2}\sigma^2 S^2 \frac{\partial^2 V}{\partial S^2} + \frac{\partial V}{\partial t} \bigg)dt$

Which can also be expressed with Greeks as:

$ d\Pi = \bigg(\frac{1}{2}\sigma^2 S^2 \Gamma + \Theta \bigg)dt$

The portfolio is hedged as time passes by, simulations are done in a weekly basis over the year.
